org.apache.ambari.server.controller.utilities

Class BufferedThreadPoolExecutorCompletionService<V>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.concurrent.ExecutorCompletionService<V>
      • org.apache.ambari.server.controller.utilities.BufferedThreadPoolExecutorCompletionService<V>
  • Type Parameters:
    V -
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    CompletionService<V>

    public class BufferedThreadPoolExecutorCompletionService<V>
extends ExecutorCompletionService<V>
    An ExecutorCompletionService which takes a ThreadPoolExecutor and uses its thread pool to execute tasks - buffering any tasks that overflow. Such buffered tasks are later re-submitted to the executor when finished tasks are polled or taken.

    This class overrides the ThreadPoolExecutor's RejectedExecutionHandler to collect overflowing tasks. When poll(long, TimeUnit) is invoked, this class will attempt to re-submit any overflow tasks before waiting the specified amount of time. This will prevent blocking on an empty completion queue since the parent ExecutorCompletionService doesn't have any idea that there are tasks waiting to be resubmitted.

    The ScalingThreadPoolExecutor can be used in conjunction with this class to provide an efficient buffered, scaling thread pool implementation.

      • poll

        public Future<V> poll(long timeout,
                      TimeUnit unit)
               throws InterruptedException

        The goal of this method is to prevent blocking if there are tasks waiting in the overflow queue. In the event that the overflow queue was populated, we should not blindly wait on the parent ExecutorCompletionService.poll(long, TimeUnit) method. Instead, we should ensure that we have submitted at least one of our own tasks for completion.
